article.description:
Wally Szczerbiak made a corner jumper as the
final buzzer sounded after Minnesota squandered a 17-point
third-quarter lead Tuesday night, giving the Timberwolves a 100-98
victory over the Dallas Mavericks.
article.headline: T-Wolves barely hold on to edge Mavericks

images.name: Garnett Kevin 030211 vert top
images.caption: Kevin Garnett, right, and Dirk Nowitzki squared off Tuesday.

article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- It wasn't just the aggressive fast breaks and the pounding of the ball into the paint that got the Minnesota Timberwolves past the perimeter-oriented Dallas Mavericks. A perfectly designed inbounds play made the biggest difference against the team with the NBA's best record. Wally Szczerbiak made a corner jumper as the final buzzer sounded Tuesday night, giving the Timberwolves a 100-98 victory after they squandered a 17-point third-quarter lead. "I hope we can just keep this going,'' said Szczerbiak, who had 21 points, nailing his shot from 17 feet to give the Timberwolves their 10th straight home victory. On an inbounds play with 1.6 seconds left, Szczerbiak set a jarring screen on Eduardo Najera for Kevin Garnett and darted to the corner. "That's the shot Wally always makes,'' said Minnesota's Anthony Peeler. Dirk Nowitzki had 34 points and Michael Finley had all 21 of his points in the second half for Dallas, which had its four-game road winning streak stopped. The Mavericks, who trailed by as many as 19 in the first half, led 98-95 on a basket by Nowitzki with 1:35 remaining. Garnett -- who had 26 points, 12 rebounds and seven assists -- converted a three-point play to tie the game with 1:17 left. Dallas had three chances to take the lead, and Minnesota had three of its own -- finally seizing it on Szczerbiak's shot. Finley, for all his success in the second half, made a mistake on the Mavs' last possession by rushing a 3-pointer that bounced high off the rim and over the backboard with 8.7 seconds left. "It was a stupid play,'' Finley said. "I wasn't thinking out there.'' Said a smiling Szczerbiak: "Oh, boy. I couldn't imagine what our coaches would say if we took that shot.'' Garnett, the MVP of Sunday's All-Star Game after scoring 37 points in 41 minutes, received a hearty ovation during the introductions and helped the Wolves surge ahead with 11 points in the first quarter. After carrying his team for much of the game, Garnett was the decoy on the final play. "They all swamped toward me and left Wally open. I'm happy for Wally,'' said Garnett, who was hugged hard by Szczerbiak in a celebration on the court. The Timberwolves blew a 22-point lead at home against Dallas last season and nearly had a similar collapse. Thirty of the Mavericks' 32 points in the third quarter came from the perimeter, and Finley had 16 of them. He made four 3-pointers (Dallas made 13 of 25 for the game) to pull Dallas within 77-73 at the end of the quarter. The Mavericks, who went into All-Star weekend with the league's best record (38-10), came out of the break looking rusty in the first half. Finley picked up two quick fouls and was scoreless. After scoring 10 of the Mavs' first 14 points, Nowitzki played most of the second period with a grimace as Minnesota's defense tightened up and he began pleading for fouls. Defensive whiz Najera, activated from the injured list earlier in the day after sitting out more than two months following knee surgery, had three fouls in three first-half minutes. Inside, Garnett, Rasho Nesterovic and Gary Trent pounded away at Dallas' skinnier post players. "They played a lot better than us for a long time,'' said Steve Nash, who had 14 points and eight assists for Dallas. For all their success, the Mavericks have stumbled a bit in big games. They've lost twice to Sacramento and blew a 30-point lead against the Lakers. "We don't care about beating Cleveland or beating the Clippers twice,'' Nowitzki said. "We want to win the big games.'' Game notes
With PG Rod Strickland (groin) out another one-to-two weeks and PF Joe Smith (ankle) unavailable for another two-to-three, Minnesota has only 10 healthy players and will probably sign a guard by Thursday to add some depth. ... Dallas also activated C Evan Eschmeyer from the injured list Tuesday. Eschmeyer, scoreless in 10 minutes, was out since November following arthroscopic surgery on his right knee.
